<DOC><DOCNO> SJMN91-06137127 </DOCNO><ACCESS> 06137127 </ACCESS><LEADPARA>  The government said today that builders boosted construction of homes andapartments by 6.2 percent in April, a report seen by analysts as evidence thehousing industry is making an erratic, rather than brisk, recovery fromrecession.;    &quot;It's kind of staggering along,&quot; said economist David F.Seiders of the National Association of Home Builders. He forecast &quot;a gradualaffair . . . not the bounce-back like we had&quot; at the end of previousrecessions.  </LEADPARA><SECTION>  Business  </SECTION><HEADLINE>  HOUSING STARTS CLIMBED 6.2% LAST MONTH  </HEADLINE><MEMO>  Financial Digest  </MEMO><TEXT>     Martin Regalia, an economist with the National Council of SavingsInstitutions, concurred. &quot;There may be some months where it doesn't improve,or actually declines a little bit, but in general, we'll see a gradualimprovement throughout the year.&quot;;    The Commerce Department said housingstarts totaled a seasonally adjusted annual rate of 957,000, up from 901,000in March.  </TEXT><BYLINE>  Mercury News Staff and Wire Reports  </BYLINE><COUNTRY>  USA  </COUNTRY><EDITION>  Stock Final  </EDITION><CODE>  SJ  </CODE><NAME>  San Jose Mercury News  </NAME><PUBDATE>   910516  </PUBDATE> <DAY>  Thursday  </DAY><MONTH>  May  </MONTH><PG.COL>  3F  </PG.COL><PUBYEAR>  1991  </PUBYEAR><REGION>  WEST  </REGION><STATE>  CA  </STATE><WORD.CT>  134  </WORD.CT><DATELINE>  Thursday May 16, 199100137127,SJ1  </DATELINE><COPYRGHT>  Copyright 1991, San Jose Mercury News  </COPYRGHT><LIMLEN>  1  </LIMLEN><LANGUAGE>  ENG  </LANGUAGE></DOC>